event.value: John Barnard describes John Boosey as "partaking in the wants of the poorest peasant, attending them in their sickness with refreshments, medicines, and all with such an abundant cheerfulness, that I think him the happiest man I know in the world."

religion.value: John is an "Elder" (minister) of the relatively new Sandemanian congregation here. By 1766 it has 37 members with 2 elders (including John).

occupation.value: Bookseller. Stated in the will of his brother Thomas.

education.value: John, a bookseller in the Clockmakers' Co, takes on William Leighton as an apprentice in the bookselling trade.
John, then a bookseller but a member of the Clockmaker's Co., takes on his son Thomas as an apprentice in the bookselling trade.

event.value: John Barnard and Samuel Pike visit and establish a Sandemanian congregation. John Popkin and W. Powell were their Elders.
John and another Elder named Davies visit to establish a Sandemanian congregation of 6 members, including John Morley who had moved from London, where he had been an active member.
John visits a new Sandemanian church which was established by Samuel Newham, an acquaintance of John's.

occupation.value: The two London-based Sandemanian congregations merge, meeting at the larger Glovers' Hall. John Barnard and George Hitchins are both ordained as Elders.

event.value: The Sandemans and John Handayside form a new congregation with George Hitchens.
Robert and William Sandeman and John Handayside, an elder from Wooler, visit London but John and the Glovers' Hall congregation are reluctant to unite with them because of some unresolved questions.

John rents the hall in order to meet with 8 other members, thus establishing the first Sandemanian church in London. Some of their time is spent praying for elders. Within six months, 14 people were members and other interested parties also attended.
event.type: Founding of first Sandemanian Congregation in London

event.value: John begins a theological discussion with Sandeman (in Edinburgh) having read Sandeman's "Letters on Theron and Aspasio" and also Sandeman's correspondence with Samuel Pike. John asks what would be required to form a church.
John meets - and is impressed by - George Glas, the son of theologian John Glas, while the younger Glas is preparing for one of his sea voyages.

John was cut off from the society for not being sufficiently humble, or, as they thought, for entertaining too exalted notions of his preaching abilities. He continued to attend their meetings for public worship until his death.
John's manuscript is published as an octavo pamphlet.
event.type: Publication of Religion of Anti Christ

event.value: The residence of Edward Gorill. Either on his way to or back from Scotland. John publicly read his manuscript on the Religion of Anti Christ, on the Book of Revelation.

event.value: Hugh was blind during the last 20 years of his life. Elizabeth Barrett Browning wrote a sonnet on his blindness.

death.value: Elizabeth Barrett Browning, his student, wrote a sonnet on his death.

individual.occupation: Greek scholar. One of his students was Elizabeth Barrett Browning. Her poem, the "Wine of Cyprus" is dedicated to him.

event.value: Not long after his arrival in Madras, Hugh was sent on a mission to Candy, Ceylon. On his return, the vessel in which he sailed was captured by the French. He was a prisoner for some months on Mauritius (aka. the Isle of Bourbon).

occupation.value: Hugh commenced a series of periodical essays, under the title of the "Indian Observer."
Hugh started a newspaper, the "Madras Courier".
Secretary to Lord Macartney, who was at about that time made governor of Madras.

education.value: Hugh would have entered the army by his father's somewhat sudden death left him unprovided for, so he chose the law for a profession instead and moved to London.

source-citation.page: London, England: Oxford University Press; Volume: Vol 02; Page: 1000

event.value: Hugh changed his surname from M[a]cAuley to Boyd following the death of his maternal grandfather. His father had already died, ~1765.

education.value: At the age of 14.
Hugh was sent to Dr. Ball's "celebrated" school in Dublin.
